              <tr><td>60%</td><td>6.32</td></tr>
              <tr><td>55%</td><td>5.79</td></tr>
              <tr><td>50%</td><td>5.26</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p>
          Again, this is an approximation. Different universities may use different
          conversion factors.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="us-gpa">
        <h2>Indian CGPA to US 4.0 GPA scale</h2>
        <p>
          Applying for a US master's program? You'll need to translate your Indian CGPA
          to the 4.0 scale. This is where it gets complicated.
        </p>

        <h3>The rough approximation</h3>
        <div class="callout formula-callout">
          <strong>US GPA ≈ Indian CGPA (10-point) × 0.4</strong>
        </div>
        <p>
          8.0 CGPA ≈ 3.2 GPA. 9.0 CGPA ≈ 3.6 GPA. This is a rough guide only.
        </p>

        <h3>More accurate conversion table</h3>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Indian CGPA (10-point)</th>
                <th>Indian Percentage</th>
                <th>US GPA (4.0)</th>
                <th>US Letter Grade</th>
              </tr>
